Eric Elliott

AUTHOR

about 6 years ago

Not all type systems are created equal, and I’m not arguing that static types are bad or a waste of time. I like static type systems and static analysis. I’m simply being realistic about the limitations of systems like Flow and TypeScript.
并非所有类型系统生而平等，我并不是说静态类型不好或浪费时间。我喜欢静态类型系统和静态分析。我只是对 Flow 和 TypeScript 等系统的局限性持现实态度。
I agree that the signal-to-noise ratio is great in Haskell, where I have never found that types get in the way. Your example comparing the type signature to a verbose comment was dubious though.
我同意 Haskell 中的信噪比非常好，我从来没有发现类型会妨碍它。不过，您将类型签名与冗长注释进行比较的示例是可疑的。
Haskell uses type variables and type classes rather than fixed types in signatures.
Haskell 在签名中使用类型变量和类型类而不是固定类型。
By contrast, TypeScript type annotations use references to particular types, and type constructors, which makes it much harder to express functional concepts like functor mapping, which is common in JavaScript. Is it possible to accurately model fmap with TypeScript? That’s a trivial task with Haskell.
相比之下，TypeScript 类型注释使用对特定类型和类型构造函数的引用，这使得表达函数概念（如 JavaScript 中常见的函子映射）变得更加困难。是否可以使用 TypeScript 准确地为 fmap 建模？这对于 Haskell 来说是一项微不足道的任务。
Further dubious evidence you present for bugs that TDD can’t find, you write a function with a constant comparison, and say that TDD can’t find a bug without knowing the constant.
您为 TDD 找不到的错误提供了进一步的可疑证据，您编写了一个具有常量比较的函数，并说 TDD 无法在不知道常量的情况下找到错误。
Using TDD, you would not write the code for the comparison without first writing a test for it, so using TDD, you would know the constant in advance.
使用 TDD，你不会在没有先为它编写测试的情况下编写比较代码，因此使用 TDD，你会提前知道常量。
Also, TDD makes checks for returned types pretty much redundant, because testing for a particular value automatically tests for that value’s return type. If it’s the wrong type, the test for vlaue equality will fail.
此外，TDD 对返回类型的检查几乎是多余的，因为对特定值的测试会自动测试该值的返回类型。如果类型错误，则 vlaue 相等性测试将失败。
I agree that static types do catch a significant subclass of bugs, but I still have not seen strong evidence that static types reduce bug density by much. Nor have I found the “infinite number of tests” any better at catching bugs than TDD.
我同意静态类型确实捕获了一个重要的 bug 子类，但我仍然没有看到有力的证据表明静态类型大大减少了 bug 密度。我也没有发现“无限数量的测试”比 TDD 更能捕捉错误。
I agree static types are useful, but many of the benefits of TypeScript are available using static and flow analysis of standard JS using type inference. All you need to do to get them is install some tools like Tern.JS and ESLint and provide adequate type hints in standard JS.
我同意静态类型很有用，但 TypeScript 的许多好处都可以通过使用类型推断对标准 JS 进行静态和流分析来获得。要获得它们，你需要做的就是安装一些工具，如 Tern.JS 和 ESLint，并在标准 JS 中提供足够的类型提示。

Michael Tiller

over 6 years ago

I disagree pretty strongly with your conclusions. Let me try to explain why…
我非常不同意你的结论。让我试着解释为什么……
Your “general conclusions” stated at the top really seem to be addressing the combination of TypeScript and Angular 2. I’ve worked on an Angular 2 project and I would agree that the combination is pretty unappealing. This is, in my opinion, mainly because the Angular team relies too heavily on decorators and dynamically typed templates and it is hard to get much benefit from TypeScript in that case. If, on the other hand, you use TypeScript with React, you get some HUGE benefits because you get static type checking all through your components. So I don’t think TypeScript + Angular 2 really shows the potential of TypeScript.
您在顶部陈述的“一般结论”似乎确实是在解决 TypeScript 和 Angular 2 的组合问题。我从事过一个 Angular 2 项目，我同意这种组合非常没有吸引力。在我看来，这主要是因为 Angular 团队过于依赖装饰器和动态类型模板，在这种情况下很难从 TypeScript 中获得太多好处。另一方面，如果您将 TypeScript 与 React 一起使用，您将获得一些巨大的好处，因为您可以在整个组件中进行静态类型检查。所以我不认为 TypeScript + Angular 2 真的展示了 TypeScript 的潜力。
Furthermore, I do not understand your conclusions about maintenance at all. I find exactly the opposite to be true. I find a code base that is not statically typed to very quickly become unmaintainable. This is largely because static typing not only provides highly specific and useful documentation, but static types greatly reduce the risk of introducing bugs as a result of refactoring. Similarly, I do not understand at all your basis for saying that genericity, higher order functions or object composition are “harder” with static types. In my experience, all of these benefit from static types and all for the same reason…I can clearly reason about the values I can expect in all these cases by using type constraints.
此外，我根本不理解您关于维护的结论。我发现事实恰恰相反。我发现一个非静态类型的代码库很快变得无法维护。这主要是因为静态类型不仅提供了高度具体和有用的文档，而且静态类型大大降低了由于重构而引入错误的风险。同样，我完全不理解您所说的泛型、高阶函数或对象组合对于静态类型“更难”的说法。根据我的经验，所有这些都受益于静态类型，并且出于相同的原因……我可以通过使用类型约束清楚地推断出在所有这些情况下我可以期望的值。
You mention runtime type checking many times. But static type checking (i.e., detecting the errors before the code is run) is in my opinion far superior to runtime type checking because the checks occur before your code even runs. Runtime checks are effectively the same outcome as throwing an exception.
您多次提到运行时类型检查。但在我看来，静态类型检查（即在代码运行之前检测错误）远优于运行时类型检查，因为检查发生在代码运行之前。运行时检查实际上与抛出异常的结果相同。
I totally agree with you about the important of TDD. But I think this concern about “bug density” is a bit of a red herring. There is a sort of “Peter principle” at work here. My assertion is the bug density will always be effectively the same because it represents the degree of bugginess developers/businesses can tolerate. People will push that as far as they can in the name of getting shit done. The real metric is productivity. As an analogy, people could have fewer accidents (bugs) if everybody drove 20 mph. But they don’t. They drive fast. In fact, they drive as fast as they think is safe. If the roads are slippery or crowded they drive slow. If they roads are dry and empty, they drive fast. Static type checking is the “dry and empty” road. Will people have accidents? Yes. But they’ll drive more miles between accidents. Similarly, there will always be more bugs. But how much progress will you make “per bug”. I would argue that static types get you farther per bug.
关于 TDD 的重要性，我完全同意你的看法。但我认为这种对“错误密度”的担忧有点转移注意力。这里有一种“彼得原则”在起作用。我的断言是错误密度将始终有效，因为它代表了开发人员/企业可以容忍的错误程度。人们会以完成任务的名义尽可能地推动它。真正的衡量标准是生产力。打个比方，如果每个人都以每小时 20 英里的速度行驶，那么事故（错误）就会减少。但他们没有。他们开得很快。事实上，他们会按照他们认为安全的速度开车。如果道路湿滑或拥挤，他们会开得很慢。如果他们的道路干燥且空旷，他们就会开得很快。静态类型检查是“枯燥乏味”的道路。人会出事吗？是的。但是他们会在两次事故之间行驶更多英里。同样，总会有更多的错误。但是“每个错误”你会取得多少进步。我会争辩说，静态类型会让你在每个错误上走得更远。
With regards to generics, I think you overstate how much “work” they are and that they make it “harder to design and understand”. I completely disagree. This is all just a question of nomenclature. Once you understand it, there is no issue. You give the example of an identity function. As pointed out by another commenter, your version is needlessly verbose. The real function (at least in TypeScript) would simply be “const identity = <T>(arg: T) => arg;”. This is just 8 characters more than the original, but now the compiler can automatically infer that the return type of the function is the same as the input argument. What you refer to as “noise” I would more charitably refer to as “information”. Type constraints that relate the return type to the input types of a function are a big deal both for checking and for documentation.
关于泛型，我认为你夸大了它们的“工作量”，并且它们使它“更难设计和理解”。我完全不同意。这只是一个命名问题。明白了就没有问题了。你举了一个身份函数的例子。正如另一位评论者所指出的，您的版本不必要地冗长。真正的函数（至少在 TypeScript 中）只是“const identity = <T>(arg: T) => arg;”。这只比原来多了 8 个字符，但现在编译器可以自动推断函数的返回类型与输入参数相同。你所说的“噪音”我更仁慈地称为“信息”。将返回类型与函数的输入类型相关联的类型约束对于检查和文档来说都是一件大事。
It is important to note that you talk about TypeScript mainly in terms of static type checking and Flow in terms of type inference. But they both do static type checking, they both do type inference and they both (can) leverage (optional) type annotations. I don’t really see any conceptual difference in the way their type systems work, it is mainly just a question of tooling and workflow.
需要注意的是，您主要在静态类型检查方面谈论 TypeScript，在类型推断方面谈论 Flow。但是它们都进行静态类型检查，它们都进行类型推断并且它们都（可以）利用（可选的）类型注释。我真的没有看到他们的类型系统工作方式有任何概念上的差异，这主要只是工具和工作流程的问题。
You correctly point out that it is possible for people to litter their TypeScript code with “any” types everywhere and subvert the type checker and have 1,000 bugs in their code. Is this an argument against static type checking? If so, I don’t think it is an effective one because it seems to be saying that if you subvert the type checker and just treat everything as “any”, you’ll mask lots of bugs because the compiler won’t catch them. Well, that sounds an awful lot like *Javascript* to me. The argument seems to be that because a terrible programmer can essentially turn off type checking and be constrained only by the *normal* runtime type checks of Javascript that the static typing isn’t worth it. I draw the completely inverse conclusion. Those checks *have* a benefit as evidenced by all the trivial bugs that were masked when people turned off type checking.
您正确地指出，人们可能会在他们的 TypeScript 代码中随处乱扔“任何”类型，并破坏类型检查器并在他们的代码中出现 1,000 个错误。这是反对静态类型检查的论据吗？如果是这样，我认为它不是一个有效的方法，因为它似乎在说如果你颠覆类型检查器并将所有内容都视为“任何”，你会掩盖很多错误，因为编译器不会捕获它们.好吧，这对我来说听起来很像*Javascript*。争论似乎是因为一个糟糕的程序员可以基本上关闭类型检查并且只受到 Javascript 的*正常*运行时类型检查的约束，所以静态类型是不值得的。我得出完全相反的结论。这些检查*有*一个好处，当人们关闭类型检查时，所有的小错误都被掩盖了。
Obviously, the choice to use static or dynamic types is one each developer makes on their own. I don’t begrudge people avoiding static type checking systems. I’ve written TONS of code in Python, Javascript, Tcl, etc. I’ve also written a lot in Java, Scala, C++, TypeScript. To me, the critical factor has always been maintainability. I feel like code written in statically typed languages has a much longer shelf-life because I can confidently *refactor* it with having that churn turn into a bug factory. For a long time, I was torn about Javascript because I thought the eco-system was fantastic (lots of code, lots of ideas, lots of innovation) but I really felt the language was weak. With the dawn of altJS languages with static type checking, I now feel like the Javascript world is a fantastic place to be. As such, I really appreciate the work done by these groups to bring static type checking to Javascript.
显然，使用静态类型还是动态类型是每个开发人员自己做出的选择。我不嫉妒人们避免使用静态类型检查系统。我用 Python、Javascript、Tcl 等编写了大量代码。我还用 Java、Scala、C++、TypeScript 编写了很多代码。对我来说，关键因素一直是可维护性。我觉得用静态类型语言编写的代码具有更长的保质期，因为我可以自信地*重构*它，将流失变成错误工厂。很长一段时间，我都对 Javascript 感到困惑，因为我认为它的生态系统很棒（很多代码、很多想法、很多创新），但我真的觉得这门语言很弱。随着带有静态类型检查的 altJS 语言的出现，我现在觉得 Javascript 世界是一个美妙的地方。因此，我非常感谢这些团队为将静态类型检查引入 Javascript 所做的工作。

I have been a lisper for 20 years and wrote in other dynamic programming languages like Ruby, Perl, Javascript, Smalltalk. Most of my professional experience is in Java & Ruby, I won’t go back to Java and I’m not interested. But I have also coded things in Haskell & Elm and in my opinion you are judging a fish for how high can climb a tree, and this is a very common mistake everyone makes when trying to use types.
我使用 lisper 已经 20 年了，并且使用其他动态编程语言（如 Ruby、Perl、Javascript、Smalltalk）进行编写。我的大部分专业经验都在 Java 和 Ruby 方面，我不会回到 Java，我也不感兴趣。但我也用 Haskell & Elm 编写代码，在我看来你是在判断一条鱼能爬多高的树，这是每个人在尝试使用类型时都会犯的一个非常常见的错误。
Disclaimer: I don’t have experience on TypeScript, but I can speak about the static type experience myself.
免责声明：我没有 TypeScript 的经验，但我可以谈谈我自己的静态类型经验。
I like both approaches with types and without types and in both communities I read comments of people that doesn’t understand the other approach, because they are different, you have to change your mind, is a different paradigm.
我喜欢有类型和无类型的两种方法，在这两个社区中，我都读到不理解另一种方法的人的评论，因为它们是不同的，你必须改变主意，是一种不同的范例。
I think there are no “untyped languages” because all languages have types of data but the difference is whether you take advantage of them or not. OO languages like Smalltalk or Ruby have types, those are classes and they take advantage of types in a different way to Haskell.
我认为没有“无类型语言”，因为所有语言都有数据类型，但区别在于你是否利用它们。像 Smalltalk 或 Ruby 这样的 OO 语言有类型，它们是类，它们以不同于 Haskell 的方式利用类型。
Without further due, let me explain.
事不宜迟，让我解释一下。
You gave a definition of “duck typing” well that definition is actually the definition of strong and dynamic typing. Because there is also weak and dynamic typing, in weak-dynamic there is no static check and no check at runtime either, so code just blowup in your face with some very low level error. But if you think of static types ala typescript like this, then you are doom to fail. This is the wrong approach.
您很好地定义了“鸭子类型”，该定义实际上是强类型和动态类型的定义。因为还有弱类型和动态类型，在弱动态中没有静态检查，也没有运行时检查，所以代码只是在你面前爆炸，出现一些非常低级的错误。但是如果你像这样考虑静态类型和打字稿，那么你注定要失败。这是错误的做法。
You also mentioned TDD, well TDD is exactly how you should think about types. When you write a Test you are defining a specification that has to be satisfied every time the test runner runs. And you have several scopes for tests, you have unit testing, integration testing etc.
您还提到了 TDD，TDD 正是您应该如何考虑类型的方式。当您编写测试时，您正在定义每次测试运行程序运行时都必须满足的规范。你有几个测试范围，你有单元测试、集成测试等。
A type is a specification embedded in your code, that represents an assumption about your code, or an invariant for the code, that is at the integration level as well as the unit testing level, (because it is embedded) and every time you run your type checker it makes sure it is satisfied and it is kept *everywhere*.
类型是嵌入在代码中的规范，表示对代码的假设，或者代码的不变性，在集成级别和单元测试级别（因为它是嵌入的）以及每次运行你的类型检查器确保它是满意的并且它被保存*无处不在*。
For instance if you are going to use a variable “money” then you define a type for money and the type checker will help you identify all the points in your code that doesn’t satisfy your original specification.
例如，如果您要使用变量“money”，那么您可以为 money 定义一个类型，类型检查器将帮助您识别代码中不满足原始规范的所有点。
When you read a piece of code the type annotation allows you make inferences for your own code and what to do with that generic function parameter, something that usually the “descriptive” name of the variable tells you, but this time is automated for you by the type system. And a good code editor or an IDE can help you discover what to do with it.
当您阅读一段代码时，类型注释允许您对自己的代码进行推断以及如何处理该通用函数参数，通常变量的“描述性”名称会告诉您一些事情，但这次是自动为您提供的类型系统。一个好的代码编辑器或 IDE 可以帮助您发现如何使用它。
The type system helps you to maintain your code because tells you where the specifications are not being satisfied, that is what a type error is. That a “test” in the meaning of Test Driven Development has failed. The difference is “types” are named tests, “first class tests” that you can use in your code.
类型系统可以帮助您维护代码，因为它会告诉您哪里不满足规范，这就是类型错误。测试驱动开发意义上的“测试”失败了。不同之处在于“类型”是命名测试，您可以在代码中使用的“一流测试”。
Types also allow you to generate code and generate tests, look at Haskell’s QuickCheck. You define a test based on the type then QuickCheck generates random data for that type specification and then tests a function. And when it finds a bug, reduces the input to a minimum value of that type that will produce that bug and tells you, what that value is, so you can then write a unit test with that value and make sure it passes. Also QuickCheck can keep generating the same value until the test passes will change the randomness.
类型还允许您生成代码和生成测试，请查看 Haskell 的 QuickCheck。您根据类型定义测试，然后 QuickCheck 为该类型规范生成随机数据，然后测试函数。当它发现一个错误时，将输入减少到将产生该错误的类型的最小值，并告诉您该值是什么，这样您就可以使用该值编写单元测试并确保它通过。 QuickCheck 还可以继续生成相同的值，直到测试通过将改变随机性。
The way to think about types is like “hints” about what a specific variable or function means. But we as devs are the ones responsible for that.
思考类型的方式就像是关于特定变量或函数含义的“提示”。但我们作为开发者对此负有责任。
Type system can catch a lot of errors, but you have to design to types to do so. They are not magic they are a logic system, just like you have to design tests to catch errors, you have to design types to catch errors, otherwise they won’t.
类型系统可以捕获很多错误，但您必须设计类型才能做到这一点。它们不是魔法，它们是一个逻辑系统，就像你必须设计测试来捕获错误一样，你必须设计类型来捕获错误，否则它们不会。
Greetings and good luck in your code journey. I hope my comment helps you, I know how hard is to get types because you feel all the peer pressure that “types are good” but you don’t see it.
在您的代码之旅中问候并祝您好运。我希望我的评论对您有所帮助，我知道获得类型有多么困难，因为您会感受到所有“类型很好”的同伴压力，但您却看不到。

over 3 years ago

First, TypeScript is not great at dealing with higher order functions. It’s getting incrementally better, but it should be able to infer types in point free function compositions, and it doesn’t do that well. For example, last I checked, you have to manually type the higher order function to get type hints. Doing so erodes some of the point-free benefits of using function composition in the first place. Type systems like Haskell handle the situation much better.
首先，TypeScript 不擅长处理高阶函数。它越来越好，但它应该能够推断无点函数组合中的类型，但它做得并不好。例如，上次我检查过，您必须手动键入高阶函数才能获得类型提示。这样做首先会削弱使用函数组合的一些无意义的好处。像 Haskell 这样的类型系统可以更好地处理这种情况。
For functions like map, reduce, etc., Haskell’s higher-kinded types are infinitely more readable than TypeScript’s template-like syntax borrowed from C++ by way of Java.
对于 map、reduce 等函数，Haskell 的高级类型比通过 Java 从 C++ 借用的 TypeScript 的类模板语法更具可读性。
JSDoc is just as good/bad at dealing with higher order functions — if you don’t try to document the lambda inline. Document the type of the lambda separately and then use that type in the description of the higher order function.
JSDoc 在处理高阶函数方面同样好/不好 ——如果你不尝试记录 lambda 内联。单独记录 lambda 的类型，然后在高阶函数的描述中使用该类型。
In BOTH cases I prefer untyped alternative over the awkward fit of the TypeScript type system.
在这两种情况下，我都更喜欢无类型的替代方案，而不是笨拙的 TypeScript 类型系统。
What’s more concerning about your comment though is that you think you need dependency injection to write testable software. That simply is not true. In fact, if you’re really concerned about writing testable software, mocking is a code smell. But that’s a whole different article.
不过，关于您的评论更令人担忧的是，您认为您需要依赖注入来编写可测试的软件。那根本不是真的。事实上，如果你真的关心编写可测试的软件，模拟是一种代码味道。但那是一篇完全不同的文章。

对于依赖项注入，我不是在谈论模拟，只是注入内存中的“存储库”函数而不是真正的实现。我已经阅读了你关于模拟的文章，我同意因为你将它导入另一个模块而模拟整个模块是不好的，因为它是强耦合的标志。因此，这种依赖关系应该注入到模块中，而不是使用高阶函数，即 OOP 中控制反转的功能等价物。

You Might Not Need TypeScript (or Static Types)
你可能不需要 TypeScript（或静态类型）

TypeScript has gained a lot of popularity since the Angular 2 project decided to adopt it and write all their documentation examples in TypeScript, but is it really worth the investment?
自从 Angular 2 项目决定采用它并用 TypeScript 编写他们所有的文档示例以来，TypeScript 已经获得了很大的普及，但是它真的值得投资吗？

Before we get into this, I’ll preface it by saying that I’m a fan of the tools that static types enable, and TypeScript is currently my favorite static type system for the JavaScript community.
在我们开始之前，我会先说我是静态类型支持的工具的粉丝，而 TypeScript 目前是我最喜欢的 JavaScript 社区静态类型系统。

I come from a background using statically typed languages including C/C++ and Java. JavaScript’s dynamic types were hard to adjust to at first, but once I got used to them, it was like coming out of a long, dark tunnel and into the light. There’s a lot to love about static types, but there’s a lot to love about dynamic types, too.
我有使用静态类型语言（包括 C/C++ 和 Java）的背景。 JavaScript 的动态类型一开始很难适应，但一旦我习惯了它们，就像从一条又长又黑的隧道里出来，进入光明。静态类型有很多值得喜爱的地方，但动态类型也有很多值得喜爱的地方。

I’m not religious about tech stacks and dev tools. I’m practical. I do consulting, and a lot of dev teams use Angular 2 and TypeScript these days. If I’m going to give them advice, I’d better know what I’m talking about.
我对技术堆栈和开发工具并不虔诚。不切实际的。我做咨询，现在很多开发团队都在使用 Angular 2 和 TypeScript。如果我要给他们建议，我最好知道我在说什么。

I strongly recommend that you adopt a similar open-minded attitude towards new and different tech stacks and tools. Believe me, you’ll learn more than a few during your career.
我强烈建议您对新的和不同的技术堆栈和工具采取类似的开放态度。相信我，在您的职业生涯中您会学到很多东西。

Being a developer means that you’re choosing a lifetime of learning new things. It’s a good idea to make peace with that right now. That doesn’t mean learn all the new things, but do be open to new things if you need to learn them for your work, or just the joy of discovery.
成为一名开发人员意味着您选择终生学习新事物。现在就接受它是个好主意。这并不意味着学习所有新事物，但如果您需要为工作学习新事物，或者只是为了发现的乐趣，请对新事物保持开放的态度。

The joy of discovery is one of the best things about being a software developer.
发现的乐趣是成为软件开发人员最好的事情之一。

A few months ago, I decided to kick the tires of both Angular 2 and TypeScript. I went all-in full-time for months, contributing to a real production app on a real dev team.
几个月前，我决定放弃 Angular 2 和 TypeScript。我全职工作了几个月，在一个真正的开发团队中为一个真正的生产应用程序做出贡献。

My general conclusions went something like this:
我的一般结论是这样的：

  1. Angular 2 has lots of stuff that’s not in React, but all those extra things didn’t make me more productive, and most of the good stuff is available in 3rd party modules.
    Angular 2 有很多 React 没有的东西，但所有这些额外的东西并没有让我更有效率，而且大多数好东西都可以在 3rd 方模块中获得。
  2. TypeScript got in the way more than it helped. It didn’t reduce bugs, and didn’t enhance our productivity, either.
    TypeScript 的阻碍多于它的帮助。它没有减少错误，也没有提高我们的生产力。

You can read more about that adventure in “Angular 2 vs React: The Ultimate Dance Off”.
您可以在“Angular 2 vs React：终极之舞”中阅读更多关于该冒险的信息。

If you’re already a TypeScript fan, you’re probably already itching to comment on this post. Before you do, please read “The Shocking Secret About Static Types”.
如果您已经是 TypeScript 的粉丝，您可能已经迫不及待想要对这篇文章发表评论了。在你这样做之前，请阅读“关于静态类型的惊人秘密”。

The gist: Static types don’t reduce over-all bug density by much, but you may still love them for the developer tooling.
要点：静态类型不会大大降低总体错误密度，但您可能仍然喜欢它们作为开发工具。

Everybody’s always talking about all the benefits of static types, but relatively few articles go into the drawbacks. Let’s talk about those a bit.
每个人都在谈论静态类型的所有优点，但很少有文章探讨其缺点。让我们谈谈这些。

How Maintenance is Hindered by Static Types
静态类型如何阻碍维护

Type annotations obviously create more syntax noise, and that syntax makes code harder to read, and harder to maintain. But the drawbacks go a little deeper. Specifically, static types can make all of these things harder (not impossible, just more complicated than they need to be):
类型注解显然会产生更多的语法噪音，而这种语法会使代码更难阅读，也更难维护。但缺点更深一点。具体来说，静态类型会使所有这些事情变得更难（并非不可能，只是比它们需要的更复杂）：

  • Generic functions & polymorphism 泛型函数和多态
  • Higher order functions 高阶函数
  • Object composition 对象组合

That’s a drag, because I use all of those things a lot, and if you’re a fluent JavaScript coder, chances are good that you use them a lot, too.
这是一个拖累，因为我经常使用所有这些东西，如果你是一个流利的 JavaScript 编码器，你很有可能也经常使用它们。

I don’t want to turn this post into a book, so we’ll focus on my biggest pet peeve about static types: generic functions.
我不想把这篇文章变成一本书，所以我们将专注于我对静态类型最大的烦恼：泛型函数。

A generic function is a function that can operate on parameters of more than one type. For example, a function that calculates sums might work for numbers, but could also work with objects which supply a .valueOf() method that returns a number (note, in JS, numbers have a .valueOf() method, which makes it possible to treat both types using identical internal logic).
泛型函数是可以对多种类型的参数进行操作的函数。例如，计算总和的函数可能适用于数字，但也适用于提供返回数字的 .valueOf() 方法的对象（注意，在 JS 中，数字有一个 .valueOf() 方法，这使得处理两种类型都使用相同的内部逻辑）。

In a language like C++ or Java, generic functions require type constructors or templates, which take type parameters in order to achieve compile time function polymorphism.
在 C++ 或 Java 等语言中，泛型函数需要类型构造函数或模板，它们采用类型参数以实现编译时函数多态性。

The syntax you need to parse then becomes multi-dimensional because the single function is really two functions: The parameterized type function and the concrete function which actually performs the behavior.
然后，您需要解析的语法就变成了多维的，因为单个函数实际上是两个函数：参数化类型函数和实际执行行为的具体函数。

In a dynamically typed language, there’s no need for type constructors. Resolving the types is abstracted away from the developer. It still happens, but it happens under the hood at runtime, and the developer doesn’t need to think about it.
在动态类型语言中，不需要类型构造函数。解析类型是从开发人员那里抽象出来的。它仍然会发生，但它发生在运行时的幕后，开发人员不需要考虑它。

The effect is that developers don’t get distracted by type constructors or template syntax. Instead, developers can use duck typing, and optionally perform runtime type checks.
结果是开发人员不会被类型构造函数或模板语法分心。相反，开发人员可以使用鸭子类型，并可选择执行运行时类型检查。

Dynamic Types Don’t Mean No Type Checks
动态类型并不意味着没有类型检查

Runtime type checks are type checks that happen at program runtime, at the moment when the type is actually used. Dynamic type checking is built into JavaScript, but it’s very relaxed, and only throws errors when you try to do something super crazy like invoke undefined as a function.
运行时类型检查是在程序运行时发生的类型检查，发生在实际使用类型的时刻。动态类型检查内置于 JavaScript 中，但它非常宽松，只有当你尝试做一些超级疯狂的事情时才会抛出错误，比如将 undefined 作为函数调用。

When that happens, your software may crash. Possibly bringing down your server in production. Oops.
发生这种情况时，您的软件可能会崩溃。可能会在生产中关闭您的服务器。哎呀。

To get stricter type checking, you can define your parameter types and then wrap your function with a type checking function.
要获得更严格的类型检查，您可以定义参数类型，然后用类型检查函数包装您的函数。

For example, with JavaScript + React, we can use React’s PropTypes for automated dynamic type checks in development mode, and even compile the type checks away for production deployment, since they’re no longer needed once you’ve verified that the correct types are being passed.
例如，通过 JavaScript + React，我们可以在开发模式下使用 React 的 PropTypes 进行自动动态类型检查，甚至可以将类型检查编译到生产部署中，因为一旦您验证了正确的类型是，就不再需要它们了被通过。

In other words, the application doesn’t need to take a performance hit to benefit from runtime type checking.
换句话说，应用程序不需要受到性能影响就可以从运行时类型检查中获益。

Here’s a stripped-down example of how you might enhance runtime type checking in JavaScript:
下面是一个精简示例，说明如何增强 JavaScript 中的运行时类型检查：

A more clever version could parse the text of the function signature and extract type requirements from default parameter values. For example, if you tried to pass a Date object instead of epoch time for the hireDate, you could throw a type error.
一个更聪明的版本可以解析函数签名的文本并从默认参数值中提取类型要求。例如，如果您尝试传递 Date 对象而不是 hireDate 的纪元时间，则可能会引发类型错误。

React’s PropTypes aren’t handled with a wrapper function like this. Since React is a framework, it can arbitrarily and conditionally insert type checks anywhere during the component lifecycle. Other frameworks can accomplish a similar distinction between development and production behavior:
React 的 PropTypes 不是用这样的包装函数处理的。由于 React 是一个框架，它可以在组件生命周期的任何地方任意和有条件地插入类型检查。其他框架可以在开发和生产行为之间实现类似的区分：

If you’re thinking this sounds like a lot of trouble compared to static types, consider that runtime type checking complexity is usually hidden inside a framework or library. The creator of the app above only needs to worry about the createEmployee() function and its required property. In other words, it can be less work than writing the equivalent static type annotations.
如果您认为与静态类型相比这听起来很麻烦，请考虑运行时类型检查的复杂性通常隐藏在框架或库中。上面应用程序的创建者只需要担心 createEmployee() 函数及其 required 属性。换句话说，与编写等效的静态类型注释相比，它的工作量更少。

Note: There are a handful of open source libraries designed to do what I’ve just described. If you’d like to contribute to an experimental one that can be easily used in any JS program with or without React, check out rfx.
注意：有一些开源库旨在执行我刚才描述的操作。如果你想贡献一个可以在任何 JS 程序中使用或不使用 React 的实验性程序，请查看 rfx 。

Will Type Errors Bring Down My App?
类型错误会导致我的应用程序崩溃吗？

Type correctness does not guarantee program correctness.
类型正确性并不能保证程序的正确性。

Type errors are not the only source of bugs, and throwing an exception is not the worst thing that can happen in response to a bug.
类型错误不是 bug 的唯一来源，抛出异常并不是响应 bug 可能发生的最糟糕的事情。

Hopefully you’ve taken my advice on using TDD. Static types are great at catching type errors, but have little effect on over-all bug density, TDD can reduce production bug density by 40% — 80%. Code review is also a very effective means of reducing bug density. Each hour spent on code review saves 33 hours of maintenance[1].
希望你已经采纳了我关于使用 TDD 的建议。静态类型非常擅长捕获类型错误，但对总体错误密度影响不大，TDD 可以将生产错误密度降低 40% — 80%。代码审查也是降低错误密度的一种非常有效的手段。花在代码审查上的每一个小时可以节省 33 个小时的维护时间[1]。

If you use both TDD and code reviews, very few type errors will escape into production.
如果您同时使用 TDD 和代码审查，很少有类型错误会逃逸到生产环境中。

Add runtime type checks to the mix, and you’ve got a 3-layered line of defense against shipping bugs. I’ve seen these strategies used to ship million+ LOC code bases with very low bug density for production apps serving tens of millions of users.
将运行时类型检查添加到混合中，你就有了一个 3 层防线来防止传送错误。我已经看到这些策略用于为服务于数千万用户的生产应用程序提供数百万以上的错误密度非常低的 LOC 代码库。

Anyone who tells you that you need static types to ship large, complex apps is full of hot air. A high-quality continuous delivery approach has a much larger impact on bug density and project success than the presence or absence of static types.
任何告诉您需要静态类型来发布大型复杂应用程序的人都是空话。与是否存在静态类型相比，高质量的持续交付方法对错误密度和项目成功的影响要大得多。

What is duck typing? 什么是鸭子打字？

Duck typing is a method of type checking that looks at the structure of a value rather than its name or class. It’s like feature detection for objects. If it walks like a duck and talks like a duck, we treat it like a duck, even if it’s not.
Duck typing 是一种类型检查方法，它查看值的结构而不是它的名称或类。这就像对象的特征检测。如果它走路像鸭子，说话像鸭子，我们就把它当鸭子对待，即使它不是。

Systems like React’s PropTypes in JS are structural type checkers, which means that the type is checked based on its shape (the names and types of its properties) rather than the name or identity of a given type.
像 React 在 JS 中的 PropTypes 这样的系统是结构类型检查器，这意味着类型是根据它的形状（它的属性的名称和类型）而不是给定类型的名称或标识来检查的。

A type error is only raised if the required features are not present. Duck typing is beneficial because at design time, you don’t have any way to know all of the future requirements of the program. What if in the future you need a rubber duck drone which can still fly and quack like a regular duck?
仅当所需功能不存在时才会引发类型错误。鸭子类型是有益的，因为在设计时，您没有任何方法了解程序的所有未来需求。如果将来您需要一架仍能像普通鸭子一样飞行和嘎嘎叫的橡皮鸭无人机怎么办？

With nominal static types, you’ll need to change the type signature of every function that uses ducks everywhere in your program — a process that is not easily aided by automated refactoring tools because the functions that need changing don’t yet know that rubber duck drones exist.
对于标称静态类型，您将需要更改程序中随处使用鸭子的每个函数的类型签名——自动重构工具无法轻松协助这一过程，因为需要更改的函数还不知道橡皮鸭无人机存在。

With duck types and certain structural type systems, you don’t need to change signatures to accommodate rubber duck drones.
对于鸭子类型和某些结构类型系统，您无需更改签名即可适应橡皮鸭无人机。

Recap

In the case of generic functions, maintenance is hindered by static types in two ways:
对于泛型函数，静态类型会以两种方式阻碍维护：

  1. The added complexity of templates and type constructors makes it harder to design and understand generic functions in statically typed languages.
    模板和类型构造器增加的复杂性使得在静态类型语言中设计和理解泛型函数变得更加困难。
  2. The restrictions of nominal static types make it harder to add capabilities to the program in the future.
    标称静态类型的限制使得将来更难向程序添加功能。

The second point does not apply to structural type systems such as TypeScript, which also checks for feature availability as opposed to name or identity checks. It does apply to nominal type systems, including Java and C++.
第二点不适用于结构类型系统，例如 TypeScript，它也会检查功能可用性，而不是名称或身份检查。它确实适用于标称类型系统，包括 Java 和 C++。

Generic Functions in TypeScript TypeScript 中的泛型函数

TypeScript does suffer from added complexity for generics. Take a look at this generic identity function in standard JavaScript:
TypeScript 确实因泛型而增加了复杂性。看看标准 JavaScript 中的这个通用身份函数：

const identity = arg => arg;

Compare that to the much noisier statically typed function in TypeScript:
将其与 TypeScript 中噪音更大的静态类型函数进行比较：

function identity<T>(arg: T): T {
  return arg;
}

Neither of these functions actually needs any type information, because the value is passed through without using any of the parameter’s features.
这些函数实际上都不需要任何类型信息，因为值是在不使用参数的任何特性的情况下传递的。

Dynamic type systems like the one built into JavaScript can optionally use static data flow analysis to infer and track the types of arguments that pass through the standard JavaScript version of the function. That’s how systems like Tern.js and Facebook’s Flow work their magic. (Note: Flow is a static type system with dynamic inference & data flow analysis capabilities… annotations optional).
动态类型系统（例如内置于 JavaScript 中的系统）可以选择使用静态数据流分析来推断和跟踪通过函数的标准 JavaScript 版本的参数类型。这就是像 Tern.js 和 Facebook 的 Flow 这样的系统如何发挥它们的魔力。 （注意：Flow 是一个静态类型系统，具有动态推理和数据流分析功能……注释是可选的）。

For example, Flow doesn’t need a type constructor to keep track of identity’s types. Edit: TypeScript 2 has added similar capabilities.
例如，Flow 不需要类型构造函数来跟踪身份的类型。编辑：TypeScript 2 添加了类似的功能。

const identity = arg => arg;
const num:number = identity('NaN LOL');
// "String. This type is incompatible with number"

Type Inference Rocks 类型推理岩石

In ES6, functions can specify default values, which can be used for type inference by compatible type inference systems such as Tern.js, TypeScript, and Flow. For example:
在 ES6 中，函数可以指定默认值，这些默认值可以被 Tern.js、TypeScript 和 Flow 等兼容的类型推断系统用于类型推断。例如：

const createEmployee = ({
  name = 'Unnamed Employee',
  hireDate = Date.now(),
  title = 'Worker Drone'
}) => ({
  name,
  hireDate,
  title
});

Here’s the signature type hint displayed by atom-ternjs:
这是 atom-ternjs 显示的签名类型提示：

In other words, you can gain 99% of the benefits of a static type system using nothing but standard, dynamically-typed JavaScript code paired with an inference-capable IDE tool.
换句话说，您只需使用标准的动态类型 JavaScript 代码和具有推理能力的 IDE 工具，就可以获得静态类型系统 99% 的好处。

One great thing about TypeScript is that when the inference capabilities inevitably get a signature wrong (which frequently happens when a function wraps another function), TypeScript allows you to manually assign an interface to something so that correct type hints get displayed in your editor.
TypeScript 的一大优点是，当推理功能不可避免地出现签名错误时（当一个函数包装另一个函数时经常发生），TypeScript 允许您手动为某些东西分配一个接口，以便在您的编辑器中显示正确的类型提示。

I wish there was an optional way to do that built into JavaScript.
我希望有一种可选的方法可以内置到 JavaScript 中。

What About Automated Refactoring?
自动重构怎么样？

Two points:

  1. Any dev tool that can grok a dependency tree and has type inference and data flow analysis can do most of the same automated refactors you’ve come to expect from static type tools. e.g., Tern.js.
    任何可以理解依赖树并具有类型推断和数据流分析的开发工具都可以执行大多数与静态类型工具相同的自动重构。例如，Tern.js。
  2. In multiple decades of software development, I can count on one hand the number of times I’ve spent more than a few minutes manually refactoring something in a way that can be substantially assisted by static types.
    在几十年的软件开发过程中，我用一只手就能数出有多少次我花了超过几分钟的时间以一种静态类型可以提供实质性帮助的方式手动重构某些东西。

What About Autocomplete? 自动完成怎么样？

Every decent editor has good autocomplete plugins available. Many support type inference with assistance from Tern.js, Flow, etc… Here’s Atom’s built-in autocomplete-plus in action:
每个体面的编辑器都有很好的自动完成插件可用。在 Tern.js、Flow 等的帮助下，许多支持类型推断……这是 Atom 的内置 autocomplete-plus 的实际应用：

What About Identifier Name Typos?
标识符名称错别字怎么办？

Any decent linter can catch those errors. Here’s ESLint in action:
任何体面的 linter 都可以捕获这些错误。这是 ESLint 的实际应用：

Conclusion

It seems to me that a lot of static type advocates are unaware of the capabilities of modern dynamic type tools, such as runtime type checking, and type inference with data flow analysis.
在我看来，很多静态类型的拥护者都没有意识到现代动态类型工具的功能，例如运行时类型检查和数据流分析的类型推断。

If you can get 99% of the benefits of static types without the extra syntax noise and cognitive overhead of type annotations, will static types really give you a net win in developer productivity?
如果您可以获得静态类型 99% 的好处而没有额外的语法噪音和类型注释的认知开销，那么静态类型真的会给您带来开发人员生产力的净赢吗？

Are static types really worth the trade-offs?
静态类型真的值得权衡吗？

In my experience, the answer is yes and no.
根据我的经验，答案是肯定的，也不是。

Yes, because the developer tooling for TypeScript is currently better than the tooling for Tern.js and Flow (last I checked). By better, I mean that the UI is nicer. It’s easier to use. Type errors show up looking like the syntax errors from the linter, beautifully formatted. It’s super useful. I’m a little in love with it. You might fall in love, too.
是的，因为 TypeScript 的开发工具目前比 Tern.js 和 Flow 的工具更好（我最后检查过）。更好，我的意思是用户界面更好。它更容易使用。类型错误看起来像来自 linter 的语法错误，格式精美。它非常有用。我有点爱上它了。你也可能坠入爱河。

In my opinion, TypeScript offers the best developer tooling experience available in the JavaScript world today.
在我看来，TypeScript 提供了当今 JavaScript 世界中最好的开发人员工具体验。

If TypeScript’s tools would provide hints and type inference for standard JS files by default, I’d use it instead of Tern.js and recommend that setup to everybody. Easy choice.
如果 TypeScript 的工具默认为标准 JS 文件提供提示和类型推断，我会使用它而不是 Tern.js 并向所有人推荐该设置。简单的选择。

Note: There’s no reason that Tern.js and Flow can’t match TypeScript’s developer tooling UX. Somebody just needs to invest some TLC in the editor/IDE plugins.
注意：Tern.js 和 Flow 没有理由不能与 TypeScript 的开发人员工具 UX 相匹配。有人只需要在编辑器/IDE 插件中投入一些 TLC。

And No, because as TypeScript works today, you need to educate developers on your team about how to properly use TypeScript, and how to keep code as free of syntax noise and annotations as possible, while still providing enough type clues and annotations to make it worthwhile.
不，因为随着 TypeScript 今天的工作，你需要教育你的团队中的开发人员如何正确使用 TypeScript，以及如何使代码尽可能没有语法噪音和注释，同时仍然提供足够的类型线索和注释来使它值得。

I’ve seen a production TypeScript project with over 1,000 type errors, absolutely littered with any annotations (the go-to escape hatch when static types get in the way). No matter how much you hear that TypeScript makes it easier to run big projects, big projects come with big teams, and developer education and buy-in is one of the hardest problems in software development.
我见过一个生产 TypeScript 项目有超过 1,000 个类型错误，到处都是 any 注释（静态类型妨碍时的逃生通道）。无论您听说 TypeScript 使运行大型项目变得更加容易，大型项目都伴随着大型团队，而开发人员教育和支持是软件开发中最困难的问题之一。

TypeScript is definitely cool. I really like it. But it comes with a substantial cost, and it wouldn’t be wise to ignore it. Before you decide to use TypeScript, take a good hard look at your team and ask yourself very carefully and honestly:
TypeScript 绝对很酷。我很喜欢。但它会带来巨大的成本，忽视它是不明智的。在你决定使用 TypeScript 之前，仔细审视你的团队并非常仔细和诚实地问自己：

  • Is your team ready for the learning curve?
    您的团队准备好迎接学习曲线了吗？
  • Will you have the discipline to invest in training and mentorship to bring your developers up to speed on TypeScript?
    您是否有纪律投资于培训和指导，以使您的开发人员加快使用 TypeScript 的速度？
  • Will you always be able to maintain that same training discipline while you onboard future hires?
    在您入职未来的雇员时，您是否始终能够保持相同的培训纪律？
  • Most importantly from an ROI perspective: Are the modest improvements offered by TypeScript really worth all that extra effort?
    从 ROI 的角度来看，最重要的是：TypeScript 提供的适度改进真的值得所有额外的努力吗？

OR:

  • Is the 99% benefit you get from standard JS + Tern.js + ESLint + autocomplete + TDD + Code Review good enough for your team?
    您从标准 JS + Tern.js + ESLint + 自动完成 + TDD + Code Review 中获得的 99% 收益对您的团队来说是否足够好？

Tip: Even with static types, you still need linting, TDD, and Code review to substantially reduce production bug density.
提示：即使使用静态类型，您仍然需要 linting、TDD 和代码审查来显着降低生产错误密度。

Bottom line: There’s no question that static types can feel good. Biting into a hot glazed donut feels good. But is it really good for you?
底线：毫无疑问，静态类型会让人感觉良好。咬一口热乎乎的甜甜圈感觉很好。但它真的对你有好处吗？

  1. Russell, Glen W. “Experience with Inspection in Ultralarge-Scale Developments,” IEEE Software, Vol. 8, №1 (January 1991), pp. 25–31.
    Russell, Glen W. “在超大规模开发中的检查经验”，IEEE 软件，卷。 8, №1（1991 年 1 月），第 25-31 页。

Want to step up your JavaScript game? If you’re not a member, you’re missing out.
想要加强您的 JavaScript 游戏吗？如果你不是会员，你就错过了。
